Food Orders Preparation Time Prediction




Intro


UpCredit is a fintech which specialises in credit assessment and B2C lending. UpCredit rellies on loan default models to minimise its risk. Models help UpCredit make a decision as to whether it should grant loans to a customer or not. Some of UpCredit’s data comes from credit bureaus as well as observed behaviour collected over a loan lifetime.

Model Assessment

UpCredit has a new client portfolio and it has two competing default models. A decision must be made on the model that will be put in production. The lending target is 80% of the customers in the portfolio. It therefore must make a decision as to which model to deploy based on a sound assessment of model performance. A description of the data follows:

model_assessment <- read_csv("Ex1 - Modeling sample.csv")
glimpse(model_assessment)

Model1 and Model2 variables are two different default probability scores. The “target” variable is the observed outcome (i.e. whether customers in fact defaulted on their loan). The “sample” variable indicates whether the observation belongs to the training, test or validation samples of the models. Having the real outcome in the data means the task is to assess model performance rather than build a model from scratch.

The following visualisations ought to help gain an intuition on each of the model’s performance. The x axes of the plots are loan default probability scores as per “model1” and “model2” variables. Each plot has two distributions, one for those customers who defaulted on their loans and one for those who didn’t (1 and 0 respectively). For each model, 3 sets of plots depict the training, testing and validation sets’ distributions.

A good model would be one in which the probability of default distributions of the customers who defaulted on their loan payments were starkly different to those who didn’t. The default probability score should reflect a difference in these two subsets of users. The less overlapping the probability of default distributions, the better the model is able to predict whether customers will default or not. Further, it would be expected that model performance would decrease from training, to testing, to validation sets (in that order) but the drop in model performance shouldn’t be too stark.

viz_data <- function(model_assessment){
  model_assessment2 <-
    model_assessment %>% select(loanid, model1, target, sample)
  samples <-
    model_assessment2 %>%  select(sample) %>% unique %>% unlist
  
  plots = list()
  counter = 1
  for (i in samples) {
    data <- model_assessment2 %>% filter(sample == i)
    medians = data %>%
      group_by(target) %>%
      summarise(median_score = median(model1))
    
    plots[[counter]] =  data %>% ggplot(aes(x=model1)) +
      geom_density(aes(fill = factor(target)),
                   alpha = 0.5) +
      geom_vline(
        aes(
          xintercept = median_score,
          color = factor(target),
          linetype = factor(target)
        ),
        data = medians,
        name = "Median Scores"
      ) +
      scale_color_manual(
        values = c("red", "blue"),
        labels = c("0", "1"),
        name = "Median Scores"
      ) +
      scale_linetype_discrete(labels = c("0", "1"), name = "Median Scores") +
      labs(fill = "Default Flag",
           x = "Default Probability",
           title = i) +
      xlim(0, 0.1)
    counter = counter + 1
  }
  
  model_assessment2 <-
    model_assessment %>% select(loanid, model2, target, sample)
  samples <-
    model_assessment2 %>%  select(sample) %>% unique %>% unlist

  for (i in samples) {
    data <- model_assessment2 %>% filter(sample == i)
    medians = data %>%
      group_by(target) %>%
      summarise(median_score = median(model2))
    
    plots[[counter]] =  data %>% ggplot(.,
                                        aes(x=model2)) +
      geom_density(aes(fill = factor(target)),
                   position = "identity",
                   alpha = 0.5) +
      geom_vline(
        aes(
          xintercept = median_score,
          color = factor(target),
          linetype = factor(target)
        ),
        data = medians,
        name = "Median Scores"
      ) +
      scale_color_manual(
        values = c("red", "blue"),
        labels = c("0", "1"),
        name = "Median Scores"
      ) +
      scale_linetype_discrete(labels = c("0", "1"), name = "Median Scores") +
      labs(fill = "Default Flag",
           x = "Default Probability",
           title = i) +
      xlim(0, 0.1)
    counter = counter + 1
  }
  return(plots)
}

Both models seem to have a relatively acceptable performance overall. Median default probabilities are, however, more stable in Model1 than Model2 across samples, which means the model didn’t overfit the training data when it was fit. In other words, the scores at the centre of the samples of customers who did and didn’t default on their loan repayment is more similar across training, test and validation sets on Model1 than Model2. This could be an effect of sampling biases and therefore is not definitive proof of better model performance of Model1 over Model2.

Even if the median scores are more similar across samples in Model1 than Model2, we observe that the distance between the peaks of the probability densities of 0 and 1 in Model2 are greater than those in Model1. That means Model2 is able to better distinguish between the distributions of those who did and didn’t default on their loan repayments. This is confirmed by the Gini coefficients of both models across samples:

samples_gini <- function(model_assessment) {
  samples <- c("training", "testing", "validation")
  samples_gini <- list()
  counter = 1
  for (i in samples) {
    samples_gini[[counter]] = model_assessment %>%
      filter(sample == i) %>%
      select(model1) %>%
      unlist %>%
      Gini
    counter = counter + 1
  }
  for (i in samples) {
    samples_gini[[counter]] = model_assessment %>%
      filter(sample == i) %>%
      select(model2) %>%
      unlist %>%
      Gini
    counter = counter + 1
  }
  return(samples_gini)
}

We observe overall higher Gini coefficients on the probability of default distributions of Model2 than Model1. This means the distribution of scores of Model2 is more dissimilar whereas the distribution of scores of Model1 is more uniform. This is a strong indication Model2 is better than Model1 at distinguishing customers who did and didn’t default on their loan repayments. For both models, however, model performance is better on the test set than the training and validation sets which casts a doubt over both models. Nevertheless, all things considered up to this point, the recommendation would be to implement Model2.

Lastly, and to finalise the decision, key indicators of model performance are to be checked considering the business requirement to accept 80% of the portfolio. Recall (how good is the model at finding defaulters), specificity (how good is the model at finding non-defaulters) and precision (what percentage of the model’s default predictions are correct) are to be compared.

For each model, customers were ordered by their probability of default increasingly. The first 80% of them is accepted and the rest 20% is rejected. A 80-20 binary flag is assigned respectively and then recall, specificity and precision are calculated comparing the 80-20 flag against the real performance flag. The difference between the two models will be the distribution of real default in the 80-20 divide based on the increasing order of the default score.

Would be best practice to look at these metrics only for the validation set, but given the business requirement to accept 80% of the whole portfolio, these metrics were calculated on the whole sample:

models_metrics <- function(model_assessment) {
  
  metrics <- list()
  
  model1_data <-
    model_assessment %>%
    select(model1, target) %>%
    arrange(model1) %>%
    mutate(n = 1:n()) %>%
    mutate(new_flag = if_else(n <= floor(max(n) * .8), 0, 1)) %>%
    select(-n)
  
  model2_data <-
    model_assessment %>%
    select(model2, target) %>%
    arrange(model2) %>%
    mutate(n = 1:n()) %>%
    mutate(new_flag = if_else(n <= floor(max(n) * .8), 0, 1)) %>%
    select(-n)
  
  metrics[["model1"]][["precision"]] <-
    precision(model1_data, factor(target), factor(new_flag)) %>% select(.estimate)
  metrics[["model1"]][["specificity"]] <-
    spec(model1_data, factor(target), factor(new_flag)) %>% select(.estimate)
  metrics[["model1"]][["recall"]] <-
    recall(model1_data, factor(target), factor(new_flag)) %>% select(.estimate)
  metrics[["model2"]][["precision"]] <-
    precision(model2_data, factor(target), factor(new_flag)) %>% select(.estimate)
  metrics[["model2"]][["specificity"]] <-
    spec(model2_data, factor(target), factor(new_flag)) %>% select(.estimate)
  metrics[["model2"]][["recall"]] <-
    recall(model2_data, factor(target), factor(new_flag)) %>% select(.estimate)
  
  return(metrics)
}

metrics <- models_metrics(model_assessment)

print(paste("Model1 Precision score is", metrics[["model1"]][["precision"]][[1]]))

We observe pretty similar metrics for both models. All things considered, therefore, the recommendation is for UpCredit to put in production and implement Model2.

A New Default Model

UpCredit needs to build a new loan default model. UpCredit acquired data which was able to match to its current customers’ data. The matched data set comprises 160 variables (nominal, ordinal, continuous and dummy variables) and the target variable which is a binary loan default variable. To build the model, all the categorical and nominal variables were dummified (i.e. one-hot encoded) and the numerical variables were rescaled with mean 0 and standard deviation of 1.

modelling_data <- read_csv("Ex2 - Data sample.csv") %>% 
  select(-X1, -ID, -Var20) %>% 
  fastDummies::dummy_cols(

  tibble(.,.name_repair = "universal")

One of the common problems in credit default modelling is the imbalance of classes in the outcome variable. Far less people tend to default on their loan repayments than those who don’t. UpCredit’s customers are no exception:

In such cases of imbalance, the signal of the minority class may be too dim for the model to learn, which can result in the model scoring all the previously unobserved cases as negative. Further, splitting the minority class into training and holdout samples means that the small subsets of the minority class may not have enough in common for the model to recognise the holdout subset as an instance similar to the training subset.

The following plots help visualise correlations and distributions of two randomly chosen numeric variables in the data. These visualisations help approaching the class imbalance problem.

In this case, even if class imbalance is greater in the training than the test set, the sheer small volume of the minority class in the test set might make it difficult for any model to get a perfect prediction on the test set. We can observe how the distribution of Var14 on the defaulting users of the test set follows similar patterns to that off the defaulting users of the training set. But the smaller amount of information of the former versus the latter is evident.

There are many possible options to build a classifier on imbalanced data. Weighting observations, bias initialisations, over or/and under sampling the minority or/and majority classes are some of the most common. None of them come without cost. For example, oversampling the minority class logically tends to result in overfitting it regardless of aggressive regularisation.

For this model, setting the output bias in the prediction layer of the neural network proved enough to achieve an acceptable model performance. A single-layer, 256 neurons network was trained. Early stopping was set at 10 epochs of the validation binary-crossentropy not decreasing any further. The model trained for ~100 epochs.

As can be observed in the charts below, a really acceptable model performance was observed on the validation set. Precision and recall increase as the model trains and the area under the ROC curve increase as the model trains. Binary cross-entropy decreases as well.

In order to implement this model, cross validation is suggested as a next step. However, given the small numbers of the minority class (defaulting customers), more data is required so that the validation folds can be stratified according to the default variable.


import tensorflow as tf
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import os
import tempfile
import imblearn
import seaborn as sns
import sklearn

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib as mpl
from sklearn.utils import class_weight
from sklearn.metrics import f1_score
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

pd.options.display.max_rows = 4000
colors = plt.rcParams['axes.prop_cycle'].by_key()['color']
mpl.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = (12, 10)

# model assessment function definitions
def plot_metrics(history):
    metrics =  ['loss', 'auc', 'precision', 'recall']
    for n, metric in enumerate(metrics):
        name = metric.replace("_"," ").capitalize()
        plt.subplot(2,2,n+1)
        plt.plot(history.epoch,  history.history[metric], color=colors[0], label='Train')
        plt.plot(history.epoch, history.history['val_'+metric],
                 color=colors[0], linestyle="--", label='Val')
        plt.xlabel('Epoch')
        plt.ylabel(name)
        if metric == 'loss':
            plt.ylim([0, plt.ylim()[1]])
        elif metric == 'auc':
            plt.ylim([0.8,1])
        else:
            plt.ylim([0,1])

    plt.legend()
    plt.draw()
    plt.show()

def plot_cm(labels, predictions, p=0.5):
    cm = confusion_matrix(labels, predictions > p)
    plt.figure(figsize=(5,5))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt="d")
    plt.title('Confusion matrix @{:.2f}'.format(p))
    plt.ylabel('Actual label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
    plt.draw()
    plt.show()

    print('Non-defaulting customers detected (True Negatives): ', cm[0][0])
    print('Non_defaulting customers incorrectly detected (False Positives): ', cm[0][1])
    print('Defaulting customers Missed (False Negatives): ', cm[1][0])
    print('Defaulting customers detected(True Positives): ', cm[1][1])

# loading data
all_data = pd.read_csv("modelling_data.csv")
training_data  = all_data.loc[all_data["Fold"] == 'IS',:].drop("Fold", axis=1)
test_data = all_data.loc[all_data["Fold"] == 'OS',:].drop("Fold", axis=1)
xtrain = test_data.drop('Target', axis=1)
ytrain = test_data.Target.to_numpy()
xtest = test_data.drop('Target', axis=1)
ytest = test_data.Target.to_numpy()

#reshaping data
xtrain, xtest = np.array(xtrain, dtype = 'float64'), np.array(xtest, dtype = 'float64')
xtrain, xtest = np.reshape(xtrain, (xtrain.shape[0],1, xtrain.shape[1])), np.reshape(xtest, (xtest.shape[0],1,xtest.shape[1]))

# define and compile model
tf.keras.backend.clear_session()
model_metrics = [
      tf.keras.metrics.TruePositives(name='tp'),
      tf.keras.metrics.FalsePositives(name='fp'),
      tf.keras.metrics.TrueNegatives(name='tn'),
      tf.keras.metrics.FalseNegatives(name='fn'), 
      tf.keras.metrics.BinaryAccuracy(name='accuracy'),
      tf.keras.metrics.Precision(name='precision'),
      tf.keras.metrics.Recall(name='recall'),
      tf.keras.metrics.AUC(name='auc'),
]

def make_model(metrics = model_metrics, output_bias=None):
    if output_bias is not None:
        output_bias = tf.keras.initializers.Constant(output_bias)
    model = tf.keras.Sequential([
        tf.keras.layers.Dense(256, activation='relu', input_shape=(None,xtrain.shape[-1])),
        tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.5),        
        tf.keras.layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid',bias_initializer=output_bias),
    ])
    model.compile(
        optimizer='Adam',
        loss='binary_crossentropy',
        metrics=metrics)
    
    return model

EPOCHS = 100
BATCH_SIZE = 2048
my_callbacks = tf.keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', verbose=1, patience=10, mode='min', restore_best_weights=True)
model = make_model()

#Setting initial bias and saving initial weights
initial_bias = np.log(training_data.Target.value_counts()[1]/training_data.Target.value_counts()[0])
model = make_model(output_bias = initial_bias)
initial_weights = os.path.join(tempfile.mkdtemp(),'initial_weights')
model.save_weights(initial_weights)
# Train the model
model = make_model(output_bias = initial_bias)
model.load_weights(initial_weights)
history = model.fit(
    xtrain,
    ytrain,
    batch_size=BATCH_SIZE,
    epochs=EPOCHS,
    callbacks = [my_callbacks],
    validation_data=(xtest, ytest))
# Model Evaluation
ypred = np.reshape((model.predict(xtest) > 0.5).astype('int'), (xtest.shape[0],))
plot_metrics(history)

plot_cm(ytest,ypred)

## Non_defaulting customers incorrectly detected (False Positives):  0
## Defaulting customers Missed (False Negatives):  0
## Defaulting customers detected(True Positives):  82
